column13: I find I'm far more likely to impulse purchase when the same thing is shown to me over and over, which happens on Instagram. I just want them to stop. I know I'm being manipulated.

It would have to reward me money or items for free, because my current purchases are almost free using coupons on chinese websites. Today I bought 20 black keychain carbiners for 0.1euro that is like 0.12dollar shipping included. I'll give some of them to my family members for easy separation from keyring and use others for my many keys.  Every day I get 1$ coupon so my daily purchases range from 0.01$ to 0.25$. And then I also get 100$ in coupons/credits every few months using the chinese apps. I got around 5000$ of items for 60$ so far. I also buy craft materials, craft items and sell them, for example natural stone beads for bracelet craft. Profits are 3000%  on many of these purchases. 

So yeah, if your app does not give me money I do not see it being interesting. I'm in large shopping community and everyone does what I do. The only thing to stop us will be new laws that will make imports insanely expensive, those do exist in some countries already.

column13: I use my bookmarks to save items I feel like buying and later go through and delete most of them. I like to me digitally minimal so I find it stressful to have items in the bookmarks folder to begin with, so it would be helpful to have something that can store the links to product pages and have the same function but I don't have to look at everyday (like if the app was a Chrome extension, I don't need any link in bookmarks; or if it was a website, I only have 1 link instead of 20). I also would like pictures because then I can easily compare the items and may not even have to click the link to know "actually I do or don't want this." I also find those extra steps you need to do to pay online are good deterrents! E.g. not keeping my credit cards saved and manually typing it in every time makes me think more about a purchase as I feel "more guilty" and "more anxious" when buying things I want but don't need. Perhaps a  popup that asks "do you really want this?" or shows how the purchase amount would affect my finances would make me reconsider those few impulse purchases that slip through the cracks of my control.
